me.wobblyyyy.pathfinder2.scheduler

Class Scheduler

  • java.lang.Object
    • me.wobblyyyy.pathfinder2.scheduler.Scheduler

  • public class Scheduler
extends java.lang.Object
    A scheduler is an easy way to automate Pathfinder's operation.

    A scheduler is responsible for managing a single Pathfinder instance. The scheduler can primarily be managed with a couple of methods...

    • tick()
      Tick the scheduler once. This will activate the next task if it can be activated. If there is already an activated task, this will check to see if the task has "expired" (if it shouldn't continue its execution) and if it has, it'll be removed from the task queue, meaning the next tick() method call will activate a new task.
    • queueTask(Task), queueTasks(Task...), queueTasks(List)
      Queue one or more tasks. These tasks can be controlled via the tick() method.

    Since:
    0.0.0
    Author:
    Colin Robertson

      • enableAutomaticTicking

        public void enableAutomaticTicking(java.util.function.Supplier<java.lang.Boolean> shouldContinueTicking)
        Enable automatic ticking until either the shouldContinueTicking Supplier returns false, or the disableAutomaticTicking() method is called.

        THE USE OF THIS METHOD IS STRONGLY DISCOURAGED. Using another thread in an application like this doesn't provide any benefits. Because Pathfinder shouldn't be performing incredibly intense calculations, there's nothing to worry about. Additionally, CPU-bound operations are not sped up by multithreading, they're just made to be non-blocking.

        Automatic ticking is starting a new thread on which the tick() method will be called repeatedly. This means you can focus on other parts of your robot in your main thread. It's worth nothing that I personally don't recommend using automatic ticking, but it's a fairly personal choice.

        Parameters:
        shouldContinueTicking - a supplier to indicate whether the thread should continue ticking. If this supplier returns false at any point, the thread will automatically be stopped, and thus, automatic ticking will stop.
        See Also:
        enableAutomaticTicking(), disableAutomaticTicking()

      • disableAutomaticTicking

      • isAutomaticallyTicking

        public boolean isAutomaticallyTicking()
        Is the Scheduler currently in automatic ticking mode? This value will return false until the enableAutomaticTicking() or enableAutomaticTicking(Supplier) method is called, and will then return true until disableAutomaticTicking() is called.
        Returns:
        is the Scheduler currently in automatic ticking?

      • clear

        public void clear()
